through late Tuesday night.', '* WIND...Sustained 15 to 25 mph with gusts to 30 mph this

Area: Benewah, ID; Kootenai, ID; Latah, ID; Shoshone, ID
Description:
["The Idaho Panhandle will receive moderate to heavy rain Monday night
into Tuesday. Increased runoff from the rain and melting snow will
produce rises on rivers and streams in Shoshone, Kootenai, and
Benewah counties. High flows on the Coeur d'Alene and St Joe Rivers
will likely linger through late week. There may also be a heightened
risk of mud and rock slides in the steep terrain of the central
Idaho Panhandle."]

['* WHAT...Minor flooding is forecast.', '* WHERE...Great Pee Dee River At Pee Dee.', '* WHEN...From Monday morning until further notice.', '* IMPACTS...At 20.0 feet, Flood waters will affect swamplands and
logging interests. Flood waters will affect timberland as far
downstream as Yauhannah two weeks after the crest passes Pee Dee.
Logging equipment needs to be moved.', '* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 8:00 PM EDT Sunday the stage was 18.0 feet.
- Forecast...The river is expected to rise above flood stage
late tomorrow morning and continue rising to a crest of 21.0
feet Wednesday morning.
- Flood stage is 19.0 feet.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood']

Area: Crittenden, AR; DeSoto, MS; Shelby, TN
Description:
['* WHAT...Flooding caused by excessive rainfall continues.', '* WHERE...Mississippi River at Memphis.', '* WHEN...Until Tuesday, March 22.', '* IMPACTS...At 30.0 feet, In Memphis, the boat landing on the north
end of Mud Island at the mouth of the Wolf River is covered. In
Arkansas, recreational vehicle park south of West Memphis starts
to flood. Dacus Lake Road is flooding north and south of I-40. The
river is against the toe of the levee from the north Shelby County
line south to near Sulcer Road. Water is encroaching the levee
near the south end of Island 40 Chute. The camp near Mound City is
flooding. Water is beginning to flood the settlement near Blue
Lake.', '* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 7:00 PM CDT Sunday the stage was 30.3 feet.

Area: Mississippi, AR; Lauderdale, TN; Tipton, TN
Description:
['* WHAT...Minor flooding is occurring and minor flooding is forecast.', '* WHERE...Mississippi River at Osceola.', '* WHEN...Until early Sunday morning.', "* IMPACTS...At 30.0 feet, In Tennessee, The Reach-Coker Slough
hunting camp is flooded. Crawford Road West just north of the Fort
Pillow Historic Area is going under water. Houses are flooding
along Cold Creek Road. Four Mile Road is flooding and Champion
Lake Road is being flooded by Hatchie River backwater. Sunk Lake
Road is flooded north of Bee Lake. In Arkansas, Highway 120 is
flooded between O'Donnell Bend and the levee, and barge loading
has to stop at Osceola.", '* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 7:00 PM CDT Sunday the stage was 29.9 feet.
- Recent Activity...The maximum river stage in the 24 hours
ending at 7:00 PM CDT Sunday was 30.5 feet.
- Forecast...The river is expected to fall below flood stage
early Saturday morning and continue falling to 12.7 feet
Sunday, April 03.
- Flood stage is 28.0 feet.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood']

Area: Jim Hogg
Description:
['Surface observations indicate that areas of dense fog have
developed across portions of Jim Hogg County early this morning.
Visibilities of around 1/4 of a mile will occur in the fog, mainly
affect the Hebbronville area. These areas of fog will likely
dissipate by midmorning.', 'Morning motorists in the Hebbronville area are urged to reduce
speed, use low beam headlights, and avoid following other vehicles
too closely in the areas of denser fog through the early morning
hours.']

Area: Mason, WA
Description:
['* WHAT...Flooding caused by excessive rainfall is possible.', '* WHERE...A portion of northwest Washington, including the following
county, Mason.', '* WHEN...From late tonight through Tuesday evening.', '* IMPACTS...Excessive runoff may result in flooding of rivers,
creeks, streams, and other low-lying and flood-prone locations.', '* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- Rain will continue through tonight, and taper to showers on
Tuesday. The Skokomish River near Potlach will crest near
flood stage around midday on Tuesday before receding into
Tuesday night.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood']

Area: Mason, WA
Description:
['An approaching  weather system will result in rain, heavy at times,
through Tuesday night with rises on rivers during this period.', 'The heaviest rain is expected to fall over the Olympics after
midnight tonight into Monday morning. Steady rainfall - diminishing
somewhat - will continue through Tuesday night.  Rainfall totals
over the Olympic Mountains tonight through Tuesday evening are
ranging from 3.5 to 5.5 inches. This could cause the Skokomish River
at Potlatch in Mason County to approach flood stage early Tuesday
morning.', 'Lower expected rainfall amounts for the Cascades has reduced the
potential for flooding on rivers flowing west of the Cascade
Mountains. Accordingly  the rivers of Snohomish, King, Pierce and
Lewis counties have been removed from the outlook.', 'Please monitor the latest river forecasts from the National Weather
Service for additional information.']
